ions will not catch signals generated by those operations, but it will catch signals generated by floating point operations executed within procedures called from inside the block.  This nuance causes BCPL-Float and uCode-Float to behave in slightly different ways -- the BCPL-Float version of Fix is a procedure call, so an ENABLE clause on a block containg Fix will work, but the Fix in uCode-Float is an Inline call to microcode, so the ENABLE will not work. z19402x2e12j\f1Fine point about FloatDebug:  The only version of FloatDebug uses the non-microcode floating point operations.  This is because the correct microcode Ram image could conceivably not be loaded when the debugger swaps in. Do not use FloatDebug anywhere except with the debugger, equivalent procedures are available in FloatIO.  The file MakeFloatDebug.cm in FloatDebug.dm is only a suggested command file for installing the debugger, XMesa users may wish to add XCoreMap.z19402x2e12j\f1 219f0 1f1 104f0 2f1 54i9IThe file BCPL-Float.dm contains everything needed for the non-microcode version; uCode-Float.dm contains everything needed for the microcode version.  FloatDebug.dm contains the modules needed for Debugger access to REALs.  All sources are in FloatSources.dm.  If you use floating point at all, you must include Float.bcd in your configuration.  If you read and print floats, you must include FloatIO.bcd.  If you use any of the procedures in FloatFnDefs, you must include FloatFns.bcd.  These are the only required modules.z19402x2e12j\216f1 4f0 268i36Iin FLOAT: (exports RealDefs)z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\iFloatingError: TYPE = {noError,FixRangeOverflow,ExponentOverflow,DivideBy0};z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\b13B2f1 7f0FloatingPointError: SIGNAL[f: FloatingError];z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\b18f6 2f7 6f0 18f6InitFloat: PROCEDURE;z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\b9f6 2f1 9f6STARTing Float or calling InitFloat sets up SD entries used by the floating point package.  One of these must be done before doing any floating point operations.  (InitFloat is called from the mainline code of Float, so it can be initialized by loading on the command line.)  Fine point: since Float: PROGRAM is no longer exported, the only ways to initialize the floating point package are to call InitFloat or to load the module Float with the command line.z19402l4269x2e12j\f7 5f0 271f1 183f0Fix: PROCEDURE [REAL] RETURNS [LONG INTEGER];z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\b3f6 2f1 24f6 2f7 12f6Fix returns the integer part of the REAL number.  If the integer will not fit into 32 bits, an error signal is generated.z19402l4269x2e12j\36f1 4f0FixI: PROCEDURE [REAL] RETURNS [INTEGER];z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\b4f6 2f1 24f6 2f7 7f6FixC: PROCEDURE [REAL] RETURNS [CARDINAL];z19402l3633d2999x2e6k72\b4f6 2f1 24f6 2f7 8f6These versions of fix return the integer part of the REAL number as INTEGER or CARDINAL.  If the integer will not fit into the type, an error signal is generated.z19402l4269x2e12j\53f1 4f0 11f1 7f0 4f1 8f0in FloatIO: (exports RealDefs)z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\b1BiWriteFloat: PROCEDURE [REAL];z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\b10f6 2f1 9f6 2f1 4f6AppendFloat: PROCEDURE [STRING, REAL];z19402l3633d2999x2e6k72\b11f6 2f1 9f6 2f1 12f6WriteFloat writes the REAL number onto the default output stream (using IODefs.WriteChar); AppendFloat adds onto STRING.  Scientific notation is used whenever the number is <10-4 or >107.z19402l4269x2e12j\22f1 4f0 87f1 6f0 57o4 2o0 7o4 1o0WFWriteFloat: PROCEDURE [rp: UNSPECIFIED, f: STRING, p: PROCEDURE [CHARACTER]];z19402l3633d2999e12k72\b12f6 2f1 9f6 2f1 52f6WFWriteEFloat: PROCEDURE [rp: UNSPECIFIED, f: STRING, p: PROCEDURE [CHARACTER]];z19402l3633d2999e6k72\b13f6 2f1 9f6 2f1 52f6These procedures are intended for use with the WriteFormatted package via the SetCode procedure.  The UNSPECIFIED is treated as a POINTER TO REAL. The PROCEDURE [CHARACTER] is used to print the output.  The STRING is a format control string of the form "[lf][.[rf]]" where brackets indicate options.  Lf is the total allowed field width, rf is the number of fractional digits to print, and the minus sign indicates left justification.  If either lf or rf is 0, as many digits as are appropriate will be printed.  WFWriteEFloat forces the output to be in scientific notation, otherwise scientific notation is used whenever the number is <10-4 or >107.z19402l4269x2e12j\102f1 11f0 17f1 15f0 6f1 21f0 35f1 6f0 426o4 2o0 7o4 1o0ReadFloat: PROCEDURE RETURNS [REAL];z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\b9f6 2f1 17f6 2f1 4f6Reads a REAL number from the default input stream (using IODefs.ReadID).  The input  may be in scientific notation.z19402l4269x2e12jStringToFloat: PROCEDURE [s: STRING] RETURNS [REAL];z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\b13f6 2f1 9f6 2f7 3f1 6f6 2f1 7f6 2f1 4f6Like ReadFloat, but termination is also caused by reaching the end of the string.z19402l4269x2e12jin FloatFns: (exports FloatFnDefs)z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\iExp: PROCEDURE [REAL] RETURNS [REAL];z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\b5f1For an input argument n, returns en (e=2.718...).  (computed by continued fractions).z19402l4269x2e12j\34o4 1o0Log: PROCEDURE [base,arg: REAL] RETURNS [REAL];z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\b5f1 9f0 12f1 4f0 2f1 8f0 1f1 4f0 2f6Computes logarithm to the base base of arg (by Ln(arg)/Ln(base)).z19402l4269x2e12j\31b4B4b3BLn: PROCEDURE [REAL] RETURNS [REAL];z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\b4f1 10f0 1f1 4f0 2f1 8f0 1f1 4f0 2f1Computes the natural logarithm (base e) of the input argument.z19402l4269x2e12jSqRt: PROCEDURE [REAL] RETURNS [REAL];z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\b6f1 9f0 2f1 4f0 2f1 8f0 1f1 4f0 2f6Calculates the square root of the input value by Newton's iteration.z19402l4269x2e12jRoot: PROCEDURE [index,arg: REAL] RETURNS [REAL];z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\b6f1 10f0 12f1 4f0 2f1 8f0 1f1 4f0 2f1Calculates the indexth root of arg by e(Ln(arg)/index).z19402l4269x2e12j\15b5B11b3B5o4 15o0Power: PROCEDURE [base,exponent: REAL] RETURNS [REAL];z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\b7f1 9f0 17f1 4f0 2f1 8f0 1f1 4f0 2f6Calculates base to the exponent power by e(exponent*Ln(base)).z19402l4269x2e12j\11b4B8b8B11o4 19o0Sin: PROCEDURE [radians: REAL] RETURNS [REAL];z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\b3f1 12f0 10f1 4f0 2f1 8f0 1f1 4f0 2f1SinDeg: PROCEDURE [degrees: REAL] RETURNS [REAL];z19402l3633d2999x2e6k72\b6f1 12f0 10f1 4f0 2f1 8f0 1f1 4f0 2f6Cos: PROCEDURE [radians: REAL] RETURNS [REAL];z19402l3633d2999x2e6k72\b3f1 12f0 10f1 4f0 2f1 8f0 1f1 4f0 2f6CosDeg: PROCEDURE [degrees: REAL] RETURNS [REAL];z19402l3633d2999x2e6k72\b6f1 12f0 10f1 4f0 2f1 8f0 1f1 4f0 2f6Tan: PROCEDURE [radians: REAL] RETURNS [REAL];z19402l3633d2999x2e6k72\b3f1 12f0 10f1 4f0 2f1 8f0 1f1 4f0 2f1TanDeg: PROCEDURE [degrees: REAL] RETURNS [REAL];z19402l3633d2999x2e6k72\b6f1 12f0 10f1 4f0 2f1 8f0 1f1 4f0 2f1Computes the trigonometric function by polynomial; good to 7.33 decimal places.z19402l4269x2e12jArcTan: PROCEDURE [y, x: REAL] RETURNS [radians: REAL];z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\b6f1 12f0 7f1 4f0 2f1 8f0 10f1 4f0 2f1ArcTanDeg: PROCEDURE [y, x: REAL] RETURNS [degrees: REAL];z19402l3633d2999x2e6k72\b9f1 12f0 7f1 4f0 2f1 8f0 10f1 4f0 2f1Good to 8.7 decimal places.z19402l4269x2e12jin FloatDebug: (exports DebugRealDefs; when loaded with your debugger, the debugger will print REALs numerically).  These are the same procedures as AppendFloat and StringToFloat in FloatIO.z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\i150I11i5I13iAppendRealNumber: PROCEDURE [s: STRING,R: REAL];z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\b18f1 30f0Converts R to a STRING, and appends this STRING to the input STRING s.z19402l4269x2e12j\16f1 6f0 19f1 6f0 14f1 6f0StringToRealNumber: PROCEDURE [s: STRING] RETURNS [REAL];z19402l3633d2999x2e12k72\b20f1Same as StringToFloat (in Floatio).z19402l4269x2e12jFloating Point Formatz19402l3633d2999x2e24k72\ub21UA Mesa REAL is a 32 bit object consisting of a sign bit, 8 bit binary exponent, and 23 bit mantissa.  The sign is encoded as two's complement, so that a double word integer compare can be used for floating compare.  The exponent is encoded as excess-128.  The mantissa is always normalized and the leading "1" is not actually stored; a "hidden-bit".  The word containing the sign bit is stored at a higher memory address than the word containing the low-order mantissa bits.z19402x2e12j